{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "25548d87",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# Multiple Polylogarithms, Harmonic Polylogarithms, Multiple Zeta Values\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook covers:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **shuffle and stuffle relations**,  \n",
    "2. **the Hopf algebra and coproduct viewpoint**,  \n",
    "3. **the hierarchy of polylogarithmic functions used in Feynman integrals**,  \n",
    "4. **a worked example for $\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)$**,  \n",
    "5. **a diagram of the functional hierarchy**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The main conceptual point is:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **multiple polylogarithms (MPLs)** are a broad class of functions,\n",
    "- **harmonic polylogarithms (HPLs)** are a special subclass,\n",
    "- **multiple zeta values (MZVs)** are special constants obtained by evaluating MPLs at special arguments,\n",
    "- and all of these are naturally described using **iterated integrals**.\n",
    "\n",
    "In modern number theory, these objects are also studied as **periods** and, more specifically in many cases, as periods related to **mixed Tate motives**.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7c26b981",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "```\n",
    "Iterated integrals\n",
    "├── Polylogarithmic / hyperlogarithmic functions\n",
    "│   ├── Generalized polylogarithms (GPLs) / Multiple polylogarithms (MPLs)\n",
    "│   │   ├── Harmonic polylogarithms (HPLs)\n",
    "│   │   │   ├── Classical polylogarithms Li_n(x)\n",
    "│   │   │   │   └── Logarithms\n",
    "│   │   ├── Nielsen polylogarithms\n",
    "│   │   └── Goncharov polylogarithms\n",
    "│   └── Single-valued polylogarithms\n",
    "│\n",
    "├── Special constants from polylogarithms\n",
    "│   └── Multiple zeta values (MZVs)\n",
    "│\n",
    "└── Beyond polylogarithms\n",
    "    ├── Elliptic integrals\n",
    "    ├── Elliptic polylogarithms\n",
    "    └── More general iterated integrals on higher-genus geometries\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "06534e6f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 1. Basic definitions\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.1 Iterated integrals\n",
    "\n",
    "A fundamental structural description comes from **iterated integrals**. Given differential $1$-forms $\\omega_1,\\dots,\\omega_n$, an iterated integral has the form\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\int_0^x \\omega_1(t_1)\n",
    "\\int_0^{t_1} \\omega_2(t_2)\n",
    "\\cdots\n",
    "\\int_0^{t_{n-1}} \\omega_n(t_n).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This framework, developed by K.-T. Chen, is the most natural umbrella for the functions discussed here.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.2 Multiple polylogarithms\n",
    "\n",
    "A standard series definition of a multiple polylogarithm is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{Li}_{s_1,\\dots,s_k}(z_1,\\dots,z_k)\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\sum_{n_1>n_2>\\cdots>n_k>0}\n",
    "\\frac{z_1^{n_1}z_2^{n_2}\\cdots z_k^{n_k}}{n_1^{s_1}n_2^{s_2}\\cdots n_k^{s_k}}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The integers $s_1,\\dots,s_k$ are often called the **indices**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.3 Weight and depth\n",
    "\n",
    "For an index tuple $(s_1,\\dots,s_k)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the **weight** is\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "  w=s_1+\\cdots+s_k,\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "- the **depth** is\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "  d=k.\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "\n",
    "These gradings are central throughout the subject.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.4 Multiple zeta values\n",
    "\n",
    "A multiple zeta value is the special case\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(s_1,\\dots,s_k)\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\sum_{n_1>\\cdots>n_k>0}\n",
    "\\frac{1}{n_1^{s_1}\\cdots n_k^{s_k}},\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with convergence requiring $s_1\\ge 2$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Equivalently,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(s_1,\\dots,s_k)=\\operatorname{Li}_{s_1,\\dots,s_k}(1,\\dots,1).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.5 Harmonic polylogarithms\n",
    "\n",
    "Harmonic polylogarithms are iterated integrals built from the alphabet\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\left\\{\n",
    "\\frac{dt}{t},\n",
    "\\frac{dt}{1-t},\n",
    "\\frac{dt}{1+t}\n",
    "\\right\\},\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "usually encoded by the letters $0,1,-1$. They form an important special subclass of multiple polylogarithms, especially in perturbative quantum field theory.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "90751189",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 2. Why there are two product structures\n",
    "\n",
    "A key feature of MZVs and MPLs is that they admit:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. a **nested sum representation**, and  \n",
    "2. an **iterated integral representation**.\n",
    "\n",
    "These lead to two different products:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the **stuffle product** (also called the quasi-shuffle product), coming from sums,\n",
    "- the **shuffle product**, coming from iterated integrals.\n",
    "\n",
    "The coexistence of both structures is the source of many nontrivial identities.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "34c9b037",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 3. Shuffle algebra\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose $I(u)$ and $I(v)$ are iterated integrals associated with words $u$ and $v$. Then their product satisfies a **shuffle relation**\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "I(u)\\,I(v)=\\sum_{\\sigma\\in \\operatorname{Sh}(u,v)} I(\\sigma),\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\operatorname{Sh}(u,v)$ denotes all interleavings of the letters of $u$ and $v$ that preserve the internal order of each word.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Small example\n",
    "\n",
    "If $a$ and $b$ are one-letter words, then\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "I(a)I(b)=I(a,b)+I(b,a).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "If one word has length $2$ and the other length $1$, then\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "I(a,b)I(c)=I(a,b,c)+I(a,c,b)+I(c,a,b).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Geometric origin\n",
    "\n",
    "The reason this happens is that the product of two simplex integrals decomposes into a disjoint union of higher-dimensional simplices. That combinatorial decomposition is exactly what the shuffle law records.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "69e0fee5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 4. Stuffle algebra\n",
    "\n",
    "Now use the nested sum viewpoint. For ordinary zeta values,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(a)\\zeta(b)\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\left(\\sum_{n>0}\\frac{1}{n^a}\\right)\n",
    "\\left(\\sum_{m>0}\\frac{1}{m^b}\\right).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Split the double sum into three regions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. $n>m$,\n",
    "2. $m>n$,\n",
    "3. $n=m$.\n",
    "\n",
    "This gives\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(a)\\zeta(b)=\\zeta(a,b)+\\zeta(b,a)+\\zeta(a+b).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the simplest **stuffle relation**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why the extra term appears\n",
    "\n",
    "The term $\\zeta(a+b)$ comes from the diagonal contribution $n=m$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sum_{n>0}\\frac{1}{n^a}\\frac{1}{n^b}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\sum_{n>0}\\frac{1}{n^{a+b}}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\zeta(a+b).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the essential difference between stuffle and shuffle: in the sum picture, indices can coincide and merge.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "14d283c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 5. Double-shuffle relations\n",
    "\n",
    "Because multiple zeta values admit both sum and integral descriptions, they satisfy both shuffle and stuffle identities. Combining them yields the **double-shuffle relations**.\n",
    "\n",
    "These are among the most important structural relations in the theory of MZVs. They generate many identities between objects of the same weight and depth, and in modern work they are refined further using **regularized double-shuffle relations** to handle divergent edge cases such as expressions involving $\\zeta(1)$.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5555f87d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 6. Hopf algebra and coproduct viewpoint\n",
    "\n",
    "A second large organizing structure is the **Hopf algebra** of generalized polylogarithms.\n",
    "\n",
    "At a high level, a Hopf algebra consists of:\n",
    "\n",
    "- a product,\n",
    "- a coproduct,\n",
    "- a unit,\n",
    "- a counit,\n",
    "- an antipode,\n",
    "\n",
    "subject to compatibility axioms.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the present setting, the product comes from multiplication of polylogarithmic objects, while the **coproduct** decomposes a weight-$n$ object into tensor pieces of lower total complexity.\n",
    "\n",
    "Schematically, for a polylogarithmic function $F$ of weight $n$, the coproduct takes the form\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\Delta F\n",
    "=\n",
    "1\\otimes F + F\\otimes 1 + \\sum \\text{(lower-weight tensor terms)}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The coproduct is useful because:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. it organizes functional identities,\n",
    "2. it tracks differentiation and discontinuities,\n",
    "3. it underlies the symbol formalism used heavily in modern amplitude theory.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bc9a649a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 7. The symbol\n",
    "\n",
    "A particularly useful truncation of the coproduct is the **symbol**. Roughly, the symbol of a weight-$n$ polylogarithmic function is an element of an $n$-fold tensor product of logarithmic letters.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{S}(\\log x)=x,\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{S}(\\operatorname{Li}_2(x))=-(1-x)\\otimes x.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The symbol captures the iterated differential structure of a function, but it forgets certain lower-weight information, such as additive terms involving constants like $\\pi^2$ or $\\zeta(3)$. Thus equality of symbols is weaker than equality of functions.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3a16eeb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 8. First-entry and last-entry principles\n",
    "\n",
    "In applications to Feynman integrals and scattering amplitudes, one often studies the first and last entries of the symbol:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the **first entry** is tied to branch points and discontinuities,\n",
    "- the **last entry** is tied to differentiation.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is one reason the symbol is not just a formal gadget: it encodes analytic structure in a way that is highly useful for solving and comparing multiloop integrals.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4adbfdb8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 9. Hierarchy of function classes in Feynman integrals\n",
    "\n",
    "A useful conceptual hierarchy is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{classical polylogarithms}\n",
    "\\subset\n",
    "\\text{harmonic polylogarithms}\n",
    "\\subset\n",
    "\\text{multiple polylogarithms / generalized polylogarithms}\n",
    "\\subset\n",
    "\\text{iterated integrals}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Special values of multiple polylogarithms give multiple zeta values:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{MZVs} = \\text{special constants obtained from MPLs}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Beyond the polylogarithmic world, one encounters more general function classes:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{MPLs}\n",
    "\\subsetneq\n",
    "\\text{elliptic polylogarithms}\n",
    "\\subsetneq\n",
    "\\text{more general iterated integrals on more complicated geometries}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Interpretation in perturbative quantum field theory\n",
    "\n",
    "- **classical polylogarithms** often suffice for simple one-loop integrals,\n",
    "- **HPLs** are extremely important for one-scale problems,\n",
    "- **GPLs/MPLs** arise in more general multiscale situations,\n",
    "- **elliptic polylogarithms** appear when the geometry of the integral involves elliptic curves, as in the two-loop sunrise integral with generic masses.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b49569cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 10. Worked example: the stuffle relation for $\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Start with the product\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\left(\\sum_{n>0}\\frac{1}{n^2}\\right)\n",
    "\\left(\\sum_{m>0}\\frac{1}{m^3}\\right).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Expand the product:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)=\\sum_{n,m>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now split the sum into the three disjoint regions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. $n>m$,\n",
    "2. $m>n$,\n",
    "3. $n=m$.\n",
    "\n",
    "So\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sum_{n,m>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\sum_{n>m>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}\n",
    "+\n",
    "\\sum_{m>n>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}\n",
    "+\n",
    "\\sum_{n=m>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Interpret each part:\n",
    "\n",
    "### Region 1: $n>m$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sum_{n>m>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\zeta(2,3).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Region 2: $m>n$\n",
    "\n",
    "Renaming indices gives\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sum_{m>n>0}\\frac{1}{n^2m^3}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\zeta(3,2).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Region 3: $n=m$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sum_{n>0}\\frac{1}{n^{2+3}}\n",
    "=\n",
    "\\zeta(5).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\boxed{\n",
    "\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)=\\zeta(2,3)+\\zeta(3,2)+\\zeta(5).\n",
    "}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the weight-$5$ stuffle relation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Remarks\n",
    "\n",
    "- The left-hand side has total weight $2+3=5$.\n",
    "- Every term on the right also has weight $5$.\n",
    "- The depths are:\n",
    "  - depth $1$ for $\\zeta(5)$,\n",
    "  - depth $2$ for $\\zeta(2,3)$ and $\\zeta(3,2)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "So the stuffle product preserves total weight but can mix depths.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6b77ee7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 11. What the shuffle side looks like conceptually for the same example\n",
    "\n",
    "The same product $\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)$ can also be expressed using iterated integrals. In that representation, one obtains a shuffle expansion rather than a stuffle one.\n",
    "\n",
    "Very schematically, one writes zeta values as iterated integrals in the letters\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\omega_0=\\frac{dt}{t},\n",
    "\\qquad\n",
    "\\omega_1=\\frac{dt}{1-t},\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and then products are expanded by shuffling the corresponding words.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, the word for $\\zeta(n)$ can be represented by the pattern\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "0^{n-1}1.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\zeta(2)$ corresponds to the word $01$,\n",
    "- $\\zeta(3)$ corresponds to the word $001$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Their product expands into a sum over all shuffles of the words $01$ and $001$.\n",
    "\n",
    "That produces a different linear combination of weight-$5$ iterated integrals. After translating those iterated integrals back into the zeta basis, one gets relations among $\\zeta(2,3)$, $\\zeta(3,2)$, and $\\zeta(5)$. Equating the shuffle and stuffle expansions yields nontrivial identities.\n",
    "\n",
    "The full shuffle reduction is more intricate than the stuffle derivation, but conceptually it comes from the geometry of interleaving integration simplices rather than from splitting a double sum by inequalities.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c7b7970b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "import mpmath as mp\n",
    "\n",
    "mp.mp.dps = 50\n",
    "\n",
    "def zeta_single(s):\n",
    "    return mp.zeta(s)\n",
    "\n",
    "def mzv(indices, N=400):\n",
    "    # finite truncation for numerical exploration\n",
    "    # indices = (s1, ..., sk)\n",
    "    if len(indices) == 1:\n",
    "        s = indices[0]\n",
    "        return mp.nsum(lambda n: 1 / (n**s), [1, mp.inf])\n",
    "\n",
    "    # recursive finite sum for simple demonstrations\n",
    "    def rec(prev_max, idx_pos):\n",
    "        s = indices[idx_pos]\n",
    "        if idx_pos == len(indices) - 1:\n",
    "            return mp.nsum(lambda n: 1 / (n**s), [1, prev_max - 1]) if prev_max != mp.inf else mp.nsum(lambda n: 1 / (n**s), [1, mp.inf])\n",
    "        total = mp.mpf('0')\n",
    "        upper = N if prev_max == mp.inf else prev_max - 1\n",
    "        for n in range(1, upper + 1):\n",
    "            total += (1 / (n**s)) * rec(n, idx_pos + 1)\n",
    "        return total\n",
    "\n",
    "    # We define the outermost index as n1 > n2 > ... > nk > 0.\n",
    "    total = mp.mpf('0')\n",
    "    for n1 in range(1, N + 1):\n",
    "        total += (1 / (n1**indices[0])) * rec(n1, 1)\n",
    "    return total\n",
    "\n",
    "# A more direct depth-2 finite approximation for the current example\n",
    "def mzv_depth2(a, b, N=5000):\n",
    "    total = mp.mpf('0')\n",
    "    for n in range(2, N + 1):\n",
    "        inner = mp.mpf('0')\n",
    "        for m in range(1, n):\n",
    "            inner += 1 / (m**b)\n",
    "        total += (1 / (n**a)) * inner\n",
    "    return total\n",
    "\n",
    "lhs = zeta_single(2) * zeta_single(3)\n",
    "rhs_approx = mzv_depth2(2, 3, N=2500) + mzv_depth2(3, 2, N=2500) + zeta_single(5)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"zeta(2) * zeta(3) =\", lhs)\n",
    "print(\"finite approximation to zeta(2,3)+zeta(3,2)+zeta(5) =\", rhs_approx)\n",
    "print(\"difference =\", abs(lhs - rhs_approx))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e34d0c08",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "The difference printed above is due to truncating the depth-$2$ sums at a finite cutoff $N$. Increasing $N$ improves the agreement.\n",
    "\n",
    "The exact identity is\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(2)\\zeta(3)=\\zeta(2,3)+\\zeta(3,2)+\\zeta(5).\n",
    "$$\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "22dbbef7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 12. Diagram of the hierarchy\n",
    "\n",
    "The following diagram shows a practical hierarchy of function classes relevant in mathematics and in Feynman-integral calculations.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "880d6ee7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 8))\n",
    "ax.axis(\"off\")\n",
    "\n",
    "nodes = {\n",
    "    \"Iterated integrals\": (0.5, 0.92),\n",
    "    \"Multiple polylogarithms /\\nGeneralized polylogarithms (MPLs/GPLs)\": (0.5, 0.76),\n",
    "    \"Harmonic polylogarithms (HPLs)\": (0.5, 0.60),\n",
    "    \"Classical polylogarithms\\nLi_n(z)\": (0.5, 0.44),\n",
    "    \"Multiple zeta values (MZVs)\\n= special values / constants\": (0.18, 0.60),\n",
    "    \"Elliptic polylogarithms\\nand elliptic iterated integrals\": (0.82, 0.60),\n",
    "    \"More general functions beyond elliptic\\n(higher-genus / more complicated geometries)\": (0.82, 0.42),\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "for label, (x, y) in nodes.items():\n",
    "    ax.text(\n",
    "        x, y, label,\n",
    "        ha=\"center\", va=\"center\",\n",
    "        bbox=dict(boxstyle=\"round,pad=0.5\", fc=\"white\", ec=\"black\")\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "def arrow(p1, p2):\n",
    "    ax.annotate(\n",
    "        \"\", xy=p2, xytext=p1,\n",
    "        arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle=\"->\", lw=1.8)\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "arrow((0.5, 0.88), (0.5, 0.80))\n",
    "arrow((0.5, 0.72), (0.5, 0.64))\n",
    "arrow((0.5, 0.56), (0.5, 0.48))\n",
    "arrow((0.42, 0.76), (0.22, 0.64))\n",
    "arrow((0.58, 0.76), (0.78, 0.64))\n",
