   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aab03c2f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 13. Differential-equation viewpoint in Feynman integrals\n",
    "\n",
    "A major reason MPLs appear so often in perturbative quantum field theory is the differential-equation method for master integrals.\n",
    "\n",
    "If a vector of master integrals $\\vec f(\\epsilon,x)$ satisfies a canonical system\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "d\\vec f(\\epsilon,x)=\\epsilon\\, dA(x)\\,\\vec f(\\epsilon,x),\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and if $dA(x)$ is a logarithmic differential form, then the solution can be built iteratively from iterated integrals. When the alphabet is rational, these iterated integrals are multiple polylogarithms.\n",
    "\n",
    "This explains the pervasive role of MPLs in modern multiloop computations.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4f15c544",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 14. Concise conceptual summary\n",
    "\n",
    "A compact way to remember the landscape is:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Iterated integrals** are the broad structural framework.  \n",
    "2. **Multiple polylogarithms** are a major class of iterated integrals.  \n",
    "3. **Harmonic polylogarithms** are a special alphabet within MPLs.  \n",
    "4. **Multiple zeta values** are special constants obtained from MPLs.  \n",
    "5. **Shuffle** comes from integrals; **stuffle** comes from sums.  \n",
    "6. The deeper organizational language is that of a **Hopf algebra** and its **coproduct**.  \n",
    "7. In Feynman integrals, MPLs form the polylogarithmic layer, with **elliptic** and still more general functions appearing beyond that layer.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "11459501",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 15. References\n",
    "\n",
    "The standard references for this material include:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Chen, K.-T. (1977). *Iterated path integrals*. **Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society**, 83(5), 831-879.\n",
    "- Goncharov, A. B. (2001). *Multiple polylogarithms and mixed Tate motives*. Preprint, arXiv:math/0103059.\n",
    "- Hoffman, M. E. (2000). *Quasi-shuffle products*. **Journal of Algebraic Combinatorics**, 11, 49-68.\n",
    "- Zagier, D. (1994). *Values of zeta functions and their applications*. In *First European Congress of Mathematics, Vol. II*. Birkhäuser.\n",
    "- Ihara, K., Kaneko, M., and Zagier, D. (2006). *Derivation and double shuffle relations for multiple zeta values*. **Compositio Mathematica**, 142(2), 307-338.\n",
    "- Remiddi, E., and Vermaseren, J. A. M. (2000). *Harmonic polylogarithms*. **International Journal of Modern Physics A**, 15(5), 725-754.\n",
    "- Duhr, C. (2012). *Hopf algebras, coproducts and generalized polylogarithms*. **Journal of High Energy Physics**, 2012(08), 043.\n",
    "- Henn, J. M. (2013). *Multiloop integrals in dimensional regularization made simple*. **Physical Review Letters**, 110(25), 251601.\n",
    "- Lewin, L. (1981). *Polylogarithms and Associated Functions*. North-Holland.\n",
    "- Brown, F. (2012). *Mixed Tate motives over $\\mathbb{Z}$*. **Annals of Mathematics**, 175(2), 949-976.\n",
    "- Adams, L., Bogner, C., and Weinzierl, S. (2016). *The two-loop sunrise graph with arbitrary masses*. **Journal of Mathematical Physics**, 57(3), 032304.\n",
    "- Broedel, J., Duhr, C., Dulat, F., Penante, B., and Tancredi, L. (2018). *Elliptic polylogarithms and iterated integrals on elliptic curves I: general formalism*. **Journal of High Energy Physics**, 2018(01), 023.\n",
    "\n",
    "For a first pass, the most practical trio is often:\n",
    "- Remiddi and Vermaseren for HPLs,\n",
    "- Duhr for the coproduct/symbol viewpoint,\n",
    "- Brown or Goncharov for the deeper arithmetic and motivic structure.\n"
   ]
  }
